defaultTo what extent does AR5 reflect the range of views among climate scientists?default&#xa0;
defaultI
default have written a paper entitled ‘No consensus on consensus’
default 
defaultthat argues that
default 
defaultthe
default scientific consensus seeking process used by the IPCC has had the unintended consequence of introducing biases into the both the science and related decision making processes.
default 
defaultC
defaultognitive biases in the context of an institutionalized consensus building process have arguably resulted in the consensus becoming increasingly confirmed in a self-reinforcing way
default, to the detriment of the scientific process
default. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWhile the IPCC’s consensus approach acknowledges uncertainties, defenders of the IPCC consensus have expended considerable efforts in the 
default‘
defaultboundary work
default’
default of distinguishing those qualified to contribute to the climate change c
defaultonsensus from those who are not
default.  These efforts have 
defaultattempted to characterize
default 
defaultthose that disagree with the IPCC consensus
default as 
defaultsmall in number
default, extreme
default, and scientifically suspect
default. 
default 
defaultThese efforts create temptations to make illegitimate attacks on scientists whose views do not align with 
defaultthe consensus, and to dismiss any disagreement as p
defaultolitically motivated ‘denialism
default’
default. 
default&#xa0;
defaultA
default large number of climate scientists disagree with the views portrayed by IPCC; many of these scientists are included in desmogblog’s list
default of almost 300 climate change 
defaultdeniers (my name is included on this list).  A reflection of disagreement with the ‘consensus’ is a recent survey
default of the professional members of the American Meteorological Society
default that found 
defaultonly 
default52% 
defaultagree
default that most of the warming since 1850 is anthropogenic, which is the principal tenet of the IPCC.  
