defaultHow effective is AR5 and the summary for poldefaulticymakers in defaultconveyingdefault&#xa0;defaultwhat is meant by defaultuncertainty in scientific termsdefault? default&#xa0;defaultI have been raising concerns
default 
defaultsinc
defaulte 2003 about how uncertainty surrounding climate change is evaluated and communicated. The IPCC’s efforts to consider uncertainty focus primarily on communicating uncertainty, rather than on characterizing and exploring uncertainty in a way that would be u
defaultseful for risk managers and resource managers and the institutions that fund science. 
defaultIn a series of three papers
default 
defaultI
default have argued that the characterization of uncertainty by the IPCC is inadequate and leads to overconfidence in the conclusions, particularly with regards to the IPCC statement on attribution. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAnthropogenic climate change is a proposed theory whose basic 
defaultmechanism is well understood, but whose magnitude is highly uncertain owing to feedback processes. We know that climate changes naturally on decadal to century time scales, but we do not have explanations for observed 
defaulthistorical and paleo climate variation
defaults, including the warming from 1910-1940 and the mid 20
defaultth
default century cooling. The competition for the theory of anthropogenic climate change is our recognized ignorance about what we don’t know about natural climate variability. 
defaultThe IPCC’s failure to adequatel
defaulty characterize uncertainty arises from neglecting to consider indeterminacy and ignorance in their assessments of confidence.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;defaultDoes the AR5 address the reliability of climate models?default&#xa0;defaultThe recently released 
defaultIPCC AR5
default 
defaultSummary for Policy Makers (SPM)
default 
defaultof the 
defaultIntergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) 5
defaultth
default Assessment Report makes the following statement:
default&#xa0;
default“
defaultThere is 
defaultvery high confidence 
defaultthat climate models reproduce the observed large-scale patterns and multi-decadal trends in surface temperature, 
defaultespecially since the mid-20th century
default. (AR5 SPM, p 9)
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe IPCC’s own analysis seems to belie this
default statement, as evidenced by Figure 11.25 
defaultAR5
default. 
defaultThis figure shows that climate models have significantly over-predicted the warming effect of CO2 since 1990, a
default period during which CO2 increased from 335 to over 400 parts per million.  The most recent climate model simulations used in the AR5 indicate 
defaultthat the warming stagnation since 1998 is no longer consistent with model projections even at the 2% confidence l
defaultevel
default. 
default&#xa0;
defaultUncertainties in climate models and their simulations are associated with incomplete
default understanding of the climate system, inadequacies of numerical solutions employed in computer models, uncertainty in model parameters and parameterizations
default of unresolved processes
default, and also unce
defaultrtainty in initial conditions. 
defaultModel outcome uncertainty, also referred to as prediction error,
default arises from the propagation of the aforementioned uncertainti
defaultes through the model simulation
default. 
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe IPCC AR5 has placed 
defaulthigh confidence on the simulations of climate models, in spite of the fact that climate models have significantly overpredicted the warming for the past two decades.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultHas AR5 sufficiently explained the reasons behind the widely reported hiatus in the globdefaultal surface temperature record?default&#xa0;defaultBased upon early (leaked) drafts of the AR5, the IPCC did not even mention 
defaultthis hiatus
default. Apparently the IPCC was pressured by reviewers and its policy maker constituency to address this stagnation specifically.  Here is the r
defaultelevant text from the final version of the AR5 Summary for Policy Makers:
default&#xa0;
default“
defaultModels do not generally reproduce the observed reduction in surface warming trend over the last 10
default 
default–15 years.
default” 
default(SPM AR5
default)
default&#xa0;
default“
defaultThere is medium confidence that this difference between models and observations is to a substantial degree caused by unpredictable climate variability, with possible contributions from inadequacies in the solar, volcanic, and aerosol forcings used by the m
defaultodels and, in some models, from too strong a response to increasing greenhouse-gas forcing.
default”  (SPM AR5)
default&#xa0;
defaultThe failure of the IPCC to predict this stagnation in warming is raising serious questions about whether climate models are over sensitive to increasin
defaultg greenhouse gases. The IPCC’s dismissal of the stagnation as being associated with unpredictable climate variability raises the question as to what extent the warming between 1975 and 2000 can also be explained by unpredictable climate variability.
