defaultIs defaultthe IPCC process an effective mechanism for assessing scientdefaultific knowledge? Or has it focusdefaulted on providing a justification for political commitment?default&#xa0;defaultI am increasingly concerned that both the climate change problem and its solution have been vastly oversim
defaultplified. I am concerned that the consensus seeking process used by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) has introduced biases and acted to skew the science
default in the direction of self-confirmation
default.
default 
default My research on understanding the dynamics of
default uncertainty at the climate science-policy interface has led me to question
default whether these dynamics are operating in a manner that is healthy for 
defaulteither 
defaultthe science 
defaultor the policy process
default, acting to hyper-politicize both.
default 
defaultI see a growing
default gap between what sci
defaultence is currently 
defaultproviding
default in terms of information about 
defaultclimate variability and change 
defaultand the information desired by decision makers
default.
default 
default&#xa0;defaultIn the 1990’s, the U.S. and other nations
default embarked on a path to prevent dangerous anthropogenic climate change 
defaultby 
defaultstabilization of the concentrations of atmospheric greenhouse gases
default, which was codified by the 1992 
defaultUN Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC)
default treaty
default. The IPCC scientific assessments play a primary role in legitimizing national and international po
defaultlicies aimed at reducing greenhouse gas emissions.
default 
defaultThis objective has led to the IPCC assessments being framed around identifying anthropogenic influences on climate, 
defaultdangerous 
defaultenvironmental and socio-economic impacts of climate change, and stabilization o
defaultf CO
default2
default c
defaultoncentrations in the atmosphere.
default&#xa0;
defaultAt the time of establishment of the UNFCCC, there was as yet no clear signal of anthropogenic warming in the observations, as per the IPCC First Assessment Report (FAR) in 1990.
default It wasn’t until the IPCC’s Second Ass
defaultessment Report in 1995 that a 
default‘discernible’
default human influence on global climate was identified. The scientific support for the UNFCCC treaty was not based on observations, but rather on our theoretical understanding of the greenhouse effect and simulations f
defaultrom global climate models. 
defaultBy 2006/2007, 
defaultclimate change had soared to the top of the international political agenda
default,
default as a result of Hurricane Katrina, Al Gore’s 
defaultAn Inconvenient Truth
default, publication of the IPCC AR4 in 2007, and award of the Nobel Peace Prize 
defaultto Al Gore and the IPCC.  There was a consensus that the science was settled, and that it clearly demanded radical policy and governmental action to substantially cut CO2 emissions.
default&#xa0;
defaultNow, at the time of release of the AR5 in 2013,
default we find ourselves between 
defaultthe metaphorical
default rock and a hard place with regards to climate science and policy:
default&#xa0;
defaultAnd finally:
default&#xa0;
defaultHow and why did we land between a rock and a hard place on the climate change i
defaultssue?  There are probably many contributing reasons, but the most fundamental and profound reason is arguably that both the problem and solution were vastly oversimplified back in 1990. This framing was locked in by a self-reinforcing consensus-seeking app
defaultroach to the science and a ‘speaking consensus to power’ approach for decision making 
defaultthat pointed to only one possible course of policy action – radical emissions reductions. 
defaultThe climate community has worked for more than 20 years to establish a 
defaultscientifi
defaultc 
defaultconsensus
default on anthropogenic climate change. However, the ongoing scientific consensus seeking process has had the unintended consequence of oversimplifying both the problem and its solution and hyper-politicizing both, introducing biases into the both the
default science and related decision making processes. 
default&#xa0;
defaultT
defaulthe framing of the 
defaultclimate change 
defaultproblem by the UNFCCC/IPCC and the early articulation of a preferred policy option by the UNFCCC has
default arguably
default marginalized research on broader issues surrounding climate change, and resulted i
defaultn
default an overconfident assessment of the importance of greenhouse gases in future climate change, and stifled the development of a broader range of policy options.
default 
defaultThe result of
default this simplified framing of a wicked problem is that we lack the kinds of information to more broadly understand climate change and societal vulnerability.  
